To judge from these and the figure in Heron's Pneu- matica (227), the organ, to the eye, presented two distinct parts, a lower case or box into which the water was poured‚ and which contained the mechanism for making it act on the air to be conveyed to the tubes, and above it a series of bronze pipes, generally (but not in the Nennig mosaic) ascending in grada- tionally adjusted lengths. In the mosaic, the performer is stationed on the side of the instrument turned away from the spectator, over which his head is figured rising: his feet and hands are not seen, but the impression given by the mosaic is that he is playing on keys, and that his feet do not touch the ground. The shape of the case both in the coin and the mosaic is hexahedral, whereas Heron's name for it, βωμίσκος, might rather seem to point to a circular shape, such as was frequent in small altars: but this is a detail which may well have varied with different makers.
